            <p>MYER S. ISAACS&#44; PRESIDENT.	JESSE SELIGMAN&#44; TREASURER.		JACOB H. SCHIFF&#44; VICE&#45;PREST.<lb/>
                JULIUS GOLDMAN&#44; HON. SEC&#39;Y.		A. S. SOLOMONS&#44; GENERAL AGENT.<lb/>
                CENTRAL COMMITTEE OF THE BARON DE HIRSCH FUND.<lb/>
                EXECUTIVE OFFICE&#44; NO. 45 BROADWAY&#44; ROOM 89&#44;<lb/>
                NEW YORK&#44; DECEMBER 1ST. 1890.<lb/></p>
            <p>DEAR SIR&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>The Central Committee of the Baron de Hirsch Fund&#44; as a guide for its work&#44; desires information<lb/> upon the following points&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>1. About how many Russians and Roumanian immigrant men&#44; women and children&#44; are in your<lb/> city&#44; and about what proportion of them have been in this country not over two &#40;2&#41; years&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>2. Have any of your organizations educated them as artisans or otherwise&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>3. What amount <emph rend="italics">per capita</emph> has been expended upon them for these or other purposes during the<lb/> past two years&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>4. Is the work being continued&#59; and if so&#44; what branches of it&#44; by whom&#44; and at what cost&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>5. Can you find employment for more of these immigrants&#63;  If so&#44; how many&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>6. Do you know of particular localities wherein ready work can be obtained for immigrants&#44; and<lb/> where they are likely to assimilate with their surroundings&#63;  If so&#44; where&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>For your information it is proper to state that the benefits of the Baron de Hirsch Fund are<lb/> intended to inure&#44; exclusively&#44; to such Russian and Roumanian Immigrants as have been in this country<lb/> not longer than two &#40;2&#41; years&#44; except for educational purposes.<lb/></p>
            <p>Its work includes&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;a&#41; Furnishing mechanics with tools.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;b&#41; Teaching them easily acquired trades&#44; or the knowledge of the use of tools&#44; so that they<lb/> may become &#34;handy men&#34; in shops.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;c&#41; Paying their Entrance Fees into Trade Unions.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;d&#41; Loaning them small sums&#44; in exceptional cases&#44; to help them to become self&#45;supporting.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;e&#41; Establishing Day and Night Schools for both children and adults&#44; <emph rend="italics">only</emph> when the local<lb/> authorities or organizations have failed to make such provision&#44; wherein shall be taught the ele&#45;<lb/>mentary branches of English&#44; and which shall include the Constitution of the United States and<lb/> improved sanitary habits.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;f&#41; Transportation to points where it is positively known there is a market for the particu&#45;<lb/>lar kind of laborers sent forward.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;g&#41; <emph rend="italics">In no sense whatever to assume any part of the present duties imposed upon Jewish Congrega&#45;<lb/>tions&#44; Societies&#44; or Orders.</emph><lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;h&#41; All moneys for the direct relief of individuals are <emph rend="italics">loans</emph>&#44; and due bills for the same&#44; pay&#45;<lb/>able in installments&#44; are to be given.  Alms&#45;giving&#44; and what is understood as &#34;charitable relief&#44;&#34;<lb/> are not to be included within the domain of the Fund.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;i&#41; To Americanize and assimilate the immigrants with the masses by teaching them to<lb/> become good citizens&#44; and to prevent&#44; by all proper means&#44; their congregating in large cities.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your kind replies to the foregoing questions will be a great aid to the Central Committee in pre&#45;<lb/>paring its plans.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the honor to be&#44; Yours truly&#44; A S Solomons<lb/> <emph rend="italics">General Agent.</emph><lb/></p>
            </body>
